nts of colour by police at school; one-dimensional, tokenistic curricula portraying Black people; and the constant barrage of overt racism from students and staff alike. She shows how systemic racism works, how it alienates and seeks to destroys a child’s sense of self. She shows how our institutions work to erase the lived experiences of Black youth and try to erase Black youth themselves. Cooper Diallo’s words will resonate with some, but should shock, appall, and animate a great many more into action towards a society that is truly equitable for all.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aHigh school studentszNova ScotiavDiaries. 0aHigh schoolszNova Scotia. 0aPolice brutalityzCanada. 0aRacism in educationzNova Scotia. 0aRacismzNova Scotia. 0aStudents, BlackzNova ScotiavDiaries. 0aWhite supremacy movementszCanada. 7aYOUNG ADULT NONFICTION / Biography & Autobiography / Cultural, Ethnic & Regional.2bisacsh  a#Ownvoices.  aAnti Blackness.  aAnti racism.  aBlack Canadians.  aBlack girls.  aBlack in School.  aBlack memoir.  aBlack youth.  aColorism.  aCultural appropriation.  aDesmond Cole.  aDiscrimination.  aEducation studies.  aEducational reform.  aFeminism.  aHabiba Cooper Diallo.  aHigh school.  aHow to Be an Antiracist.  aIbram X Kendi.  aIjeoma Oluo.  aInjustice.  aIntersectional.  aIntersectionality.  aLayla F Saad.  aMe and White Supremacy.  aMisogyny.  aOwn voices.  aPolicing Black Lives.  aRace.  aRacial justice.  aRacism.  aRacist.  aRobin DiAngelo.  aSo You Want to Talk About Race.  aStamped.  aThe Hate U Give.  aThe Skin We’re In.  aThis Book Is Anti-Racist.  aWhite Fragility.  aaffirmative action.  ablack authors books for adults.  ablack in school book.  abooks black authors.  aclassroom management.  